f-WTCServer_WTCExport-a-EJBName-help: The complete name of the EJB home interface to use when invoking a service. If not specified, the default interface used is tuxedo.services.servicenameHome. For example: If the service being invoked is TOUPPER and EJBName attribute is not specified, the home interface looked up in JNDI would be tuxedo.services.TOUPPERHome.
a-EagerTrackingOfResourceMetricsEnabled-: Eager Tracking Of Resource Metrics Enabled
a-EnableEeCompliantClassloadingForEmbedd: Enable Ee Compliant Classloading For Embedded Adapters
a-EnableGroupMembershipLookupHierarchyCa: Enable Group Membership Lookup Hierarchy Caching
a-EnableSIDtoGroupLookupCaching-label: Enable SI Dto Group Lookup Caching
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: Specifies whether custom Coherence logging is enabled.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDr: The value of the encrypted property value.
a-ErrorDestination-help: The name of the target error destination for messages that have expired or reached their redelivery limit. If no error destination is configured, then such messages are simply dropped. If a message has expired or reached its redelivery limit, and the Expiration Policy is set to Redirect, then the message is moved to the specified Error Destination. For standalone destinations, an error destination must be another standalone destination that is targeted to the same JMS server as the destinations for which the error destination is defined. For uniform distributed destinations (UDDs), the error destination must be another UDD that shares the same subdeployment (i.e., targets) as the current UDD.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: The name of the error destination that should be used for members who have the same SubDeploymentName. If this value is not set then the value from the templates DeliveryFailureParamsBean will be used if it is set.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The events directory for the default persistence environment used to store durable events. If no value is specified, the directory which will be used is the coherence/events sub-directory under Domain Home directory.
a-ExactlyOnceLoadBalancingPolicy-help: Controls the load balancing behavior when the SAF service forwards messages to a distributed destination with the Exactly-Once quality of service (QOS).
a-ExpirationLoggingPolicy-help: The policy that defines what information about the message is logged when the Expiration Policy is set to Log. When specifying multiple values, enter them as a comma-separated list. The %header% and %properties% values are not case sensitive. For example, you could use "%header%,%properties%" for all the JMS header fields and user properties. However, the enumeration of individual JMS header fields and user-defined properties are case sensitive. To enumerate only individual JMS header fields you could use "%header, name, address, city, state, zip". Note: The JMSMessageID field is always logged and cannot be turned off. Therefore, if the Expiration Logging Policy is not defined (i.e., null) or is defined as an empty string, then the output to the log file contains only the JMSMessageID of the message.
a-ExpirationPolicy-help: The message Expiration Policy to use when an expired message is encountered on a destination. It is illegal to use the Redirect policy when there is no valid error destination defined for the destination. Similarly, it is illegal to remove the error destination for a destination that is using the Redirect policy. Note: The Maximum Message quota is only enforced for sending new messages. It is ignored when moving messages because of the Redirect policy.
f-JMSServer-a-ExpirationScanInterval-hel: The number of seconds between this JMS server's cycles of scanning local destinations for expired messages. A value of 0 disables active scanning. A very large scan interval effectively disables active scanning. With scanning disabled, users still do not receive expired messages and any expired messages that are discovered by other system activities are removed. However, expired messages sitting in idle destinations (such as an inactive queue or disconnected durable subscriber) are not removed and continue to consume system resources.
a-ExtraEjbcOptions-help: The extra options passed to ejbc during the dynamic ejbc of a jar file. For example: -J-mx128m By default this value is null. If no ExtraEJBCOptions are specified on the EJBComponent, the default will be pulled from the Server.ExtraEJBCOptions.
a-ExtraRmicOptions-help: The extra options passed to rmic during server-side generation are noted here. The default for this attribute must be null. If no ExtraRmicOptions are specified on the EJBComponent, the default will be pulled from Server.ExtraRmicOptions.
f-FileStore-a-FailOverLimit-help: Specify a limit for the number of cluster-targeted JMS artifact instances that can fail over to a particular JVM. This can be used to prevent too many instances from starting on a server, avoiding a system failure when starting too few servers of a formerly large cluster. A typical limit value should allow all instances to run in the smallest desired cluster size, which means (smallest-cluster-size * (limit + 1)) should equal or exceed the total number of instances. A value of -1 means there is no fail over limit (unlimited). A value of 0 prevents any fail overs of cluster-targeted JMS artifact instances, so no more than 1 instance will run per server (this is an instance that has not failed over). A value of 1 allows one fail-over instance on each server, so no more than two instances will run per server (one failed over instance plus an instance that has not failed over).
f-JDBCStore-a-FailOverLimit-help: Specify a limit for the number of cluster-targeted JMS artifact instances that can fail over to a particular JVM. This can be used to prevent too many instances from starting on a server, avoiding a system failure when starting too few servers of a formerly large cluster. A typical limit value should allow all instances to run in the smallest desired cluster size, which means (smallest-cluster-size * (limit + 1)) should equal or exceed the total number of instances. A value of -1 means there is no fail over limit (unlimited). A value of 0 prevents any fail overs of cluster-targeted JMS artifact instances, so no more than 1 instance will run per server (this is an instance that has not failed over). A value of 1 allows one fail-over instance on each server, so no more than two instances will run per server (one failed over instance plus an instance that has not failed over).
f-MessagingBridge-a-FailOverLimit-help: Specify a limit for the number of cluster-targeted JMS artifact instances that can fail over to a particular JVM. This can be used to prevent too many instances from starting on a server, avoiding a system failure when starting too few servers of a formerly large cluster. A typical limit value should allow all instances to run in the smallest desired cluster size, which means (smallest-cluster-size * (limit + 1)) should equal or exceed the total number of instances. A value of -1 means there is no fail over limit (unlimited). A value of 0 prevents any fail overs of cluster-targeted JMS artifact instances, so no more than 1 instance will run per server (this is an instance that has not failed over). A value of 1 allows one fail-over instance on each server, so no more than two instances will run per server (one failed over instance plus an instance that has not failed over).
f-FileStore-a-FailbackDelaySeconds-help: Specifies the amount of time, in seconds, to delay before failing a cluster-targeted JMS artifact instance back to its preferred server after the preferred server failed and was restarted. This delay allows time for the system to stabilize and dependent services to be restarted, preventing a system failure during a reboot. A value > 0 specifies the time, in seconds, to delay before failing a JMS artifact back to its user preferred server. A value of 0 indicates that the instance would never failback. A value of -1 indicates that there is no delay and the instance would failback immediately.
f-JDBCStore-a-FailbackDelaySeconds-help: Specifies the amount of time, in seconds, to delay before failing a cluster-targeted JMS artifact instance back to its preferred server after the preferred server failed and was restarted. This delay allows time for the system to stabilize and dependent services to be restarted, preventing a system failure during a reboot. A value > 0 specifies the time, in seconds, to delay before failing a JMS artifact back to its user preferred server. A value of 0 indicates that the instance would never failback. A value of -1 indicates that there is no delay and the instance would failback immediately.
f-MessagingBridge-a-FailbackDelaySeconds: Specifies the amount of time, in seconds, to delay before failing a cluster-targeted JMS artifact instance back to its preferred server after the preferred server failed and was restarted. This delay allows time for the system to stabilize and dependent services to be restarted, preventing a system failure during a reboot. A value > 0 specifies the time, in seconds, to delay before failing a JMS artifact back to its user preferred server. A value of 0 indicates that the instance would never failback. A value of -1 indicates that there is no delay and the instance would failback immediately.
f-JoltConnectionPool-a-FailoverAddress-h: The list of Jolt Server Listeners (JSLs) addresses that is used if the connection pool cannot establish connections to the Primary Addresses, or if the primary connections fail. The format of each address is: //hostname:port. Multiple addresses should be separated by commas. These JSLs need not reside on the same host as the primary JSLs.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDa: For multi data sources with the failover algorithm, enables the multi data source to failover connection requests to the next data source if all connections in the current data source are in use.
f-StartupClass-a-FailureIsFatal-help: Specifies whether a failure in this startup class prevents the targeted server(s) from starting. If you specify that failure is not fatal, if the startup class fails, the server continues its startup process.
f-SelfTuning_FairShareRequestClass-a-Fai: Fair share value between 1 and 1000. The default value is 50.
f-SelfTuning_WorkManager-a-FairShareRequ: The name of the FairShareRequestClass that defines the fair share value to use for this request class. One of the components of work managers is a request class that indicates the proportional of the total server thread use time this request class gets. The default fair share value is 50.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCOr: Enables the data source to subscribe to and process Oracle FAN (Fast Application Notification) events. This attribute is only applicable for RAC configurations that publish FAN notification events using the ONS protocol.
a-FannedOutRequestMaxWaitMillis-label: Fanned Out Request Max Wait Millis
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: Specifies a comma-separated list of error codes that are treated as fatal errors. These errors include deployment errors that cause a server to fail to boot and connection errors that prevent a connection from being put back in the connection pool. This optional attribute is used to define fatal error codes, that when specified as the exception code within a SQLException (retrieved by sqlException.getErrorCode()), indicate that a fatal error has occurred and the connection is no longer usable
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-Federation: The context at which this remote Tuxedo access point federates to a foreign name service. If omitted, the default federation point is tuxedo.domains.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The federation topology to use.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-Federation: The URL for a foreign name service that is federated into JNDI. Note that the WebLogic Tuxedo Connector can federate to non-CORBA service providers. If this value is not specified, the WebLogic Tuxedo Connector assumes there is a CosNaming server in the foreign domain and federates to the CosNaming server using TGIOP.
f-JMSServer_JmsMessageLogFile-a-FileCoun: The maximum number of log files that the server creates when it rotates the log. This number does not include the file that the server uses to store current messages. (Requires that you enable Number of Files Limited.)
f-SAFAgent_JmssafMessageLogFile-a-FileCo: The maximum number of log files that the server creates when it rotates the log. This number does not include the file that the server uses to store current messages. (Requires that you enable Number of Files Limited.)
f-FileStore-a-FileLockingEnabled-help: Determines whether OS file locking is used. When file locking protection is enabled, a store boot fails if another store instance already has opened the store files. Do not disable this setting unless you have procedures in place to prevent multiple store instances from opening the same file. File locking is not required but helps prevent corruption in the event that two same-named file store instances attempt to operate in the same directories. This setting applies to both primary and cache files.
f-JMSServer_JmsMessageLogFile-a-FileMinS: The size (1 - 2097150 kilobytes) that triggers the server to move log messages to a separate file. The default is 500 kilobytes. After the log file reaches the specified minimum size, the next time the server checks the file size, it will rename the current log file as SERVER_NAME.lognnnnn and create a new one to store subsequent messages. (Requires that you specify a file rotation type of Size.)
f-SAFAgent_JmssafMessageLogFile-a-FileMi: The size (1 - 2097150 kilobytes) that triggers the server to move log messages to a separate file. The default is 500 kilobytes. After the log file reaches the specified minimum size, the next time the server checks the file size, it will rename the current log file as SERVER_NAME.lognnnnn and create a new one to store subsequent messages. (Requires that you specify a file rotation type of Size.)
f-JMSServer_JmsMessageLogFile-a-FileName: The name of the file that stores current JMS server log messages. Usually it is a computed value based on the name of the parent of this MBean. For example, for a JMS server log, it is jmsserverName.log. However, if the name of the parent cannot be obtained, the file name is weblogic.log. If you specify a relative pathname, it is interpreted as relative to the server's root directory.
f-SAFAgent_JmssafMessageLogFile-a-FileNa: The name of the file that stores current SAF agent log messages.
f-JMSServer_JmsMessageLogFile-a-FileTime: The interval (in hours) at which the server saves old log messages to another file. (Requires that you specify a file rotation type of TIME.)
f-SAFAgent_JmssafMessageLogFile-a-FileTi: The interval (in hours) at which the server saves old log messages to another file. (Requires that you specify a file rotation type of TIME.)
f-JMSServer_JmsMessageLogFile-a-FileTime: This factor is defined so that log rotation can be tested at a different frequency. The default value is 3600000.
f-SAFAgent_JmssafMessageLogFile-a-FileTi: This factor is defined so that log rotation can be tested at a different frequency. The default value is 3600000.
a-FldTbl16Class-help: The names of FldTbl16Classes that are loaded via a class loader and added to a FldTbl array. Use the fully-qualified class names.  Use a comma to separate multiple entries.
a-FldTbl32Class-help: The names of FldTbl32Classes that are loaded via a class loader and added to a FldTbl array. Use the fully-qualified class names.  Use a comma to separate multiple entries.
a-FlowControlEnabled-help: Specifies whether a producer created using a connection factory allows flow control. If true, the associated message producers will be slowed down if a JMS server or a destination reaches its specified upper byte or message threshold.
a-FlowInterval-help: The adjustment period of time, in seconds, when a producer adjusts its flow from the FlowMaximum number of messages to the FlowMinimum amount, or vice versa. When a producer is flow controlled, it is slowed down from its FlowMaximum to its FlowMinimum over the specified FlowInterval amount of seconds.
a-FlowMaximum-help: The maximum number of messages-per-second allowed for a producer that is experiencing a threshold condition. When a producer is flow controlled it will never be allowed to go faster than the FlowMaximum messages per second. If a producer is not currently limiting its flow when a threshold condition is reached, the initial flow limit for that producer is set to FlowMaximum. If a producer is already limiting its flow when a threshold condition is reached (the flow limit is less than FlowMaximum), then the producer will continue at its current flow limit until the next time the flow is evaluated.
a-FlowMinimum-help: The minimum number of messages-per-second allowed for a producer that is experiencing a threshold condition. This is the lower boundary of a producer's flow limit. That is, WebLogic JMS will not further slow down a producer whose message flow limit is at its FlowMinimum. When a producer is flow controlled it will never be required to go slower than FlowMinimum messages per second.
a-FlowSteps-help: The number of steps used when a producer is adjusting its flow from the Flow Maximum amount of messages to the Flow Minimum amount, or vice versa. Specifically, the Flow Interval adjustment period is divided into the number of Flow Steps (for example, 60 seconds divided by 6 steps is 10 seconds per step).
a-ForceShutdownTimeoutNumOfThreadDump-la: Force Shutdown Timeout Num Of Thread Dump
a-ForceShutdownTimeoutThreadDumpInterval: Force Shutdown Timeout Thread Dump Interval
a-FormAuthXFrameOptionsHeaderValue-label: Form Auth X Frame Options Header Value
a-ForwardDelay-help: The number of seconds after which a uniform distributed queue member with no consumers will wait before forwarding its messages to other uniform distributed queue members that do have consumers. The default value of -1 disables this feature so that no messages are forwarded to other uniform distributed queue members. Note: This attribute is ignored by standalone/singleton Queues, it only applies to distributed queues.
f-SAFAgent-a-ForwardingPausedAtStartup-h: Specifies whether the agent is paused for forwarding messages at the startup time. When enabled, the sending agent forwards messages. Otherwise, the sending agent does not forward any messages. If the value is changed and activated, you need to restart any servers to which the MBean is targeted before the value will take effect.
a-ForwardingPolicy-help: The uniform distributed topic message Forwarding Policy specifies whether a sent message is forwarded to all members. Note: This attribute is ignored by standalone/singleton Topics, it only applies to distributed topics.
a-GlobalSocketProvider-help: Specify the Global Socket Provider name. If not specified and secured production mode is enabled, Coherence uses WebLogic SSL configuration as Global Socket Provider. Otherwise, use the specified Global Socket Provider. Prior to 14.1.2, this parameter is expected to be a boolean instead of a string so make sure to enter "true" or "false" for the value.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDa: Determines the transaction protocol (global transaction processing behavior) for the data source.
f-SelfTuning_ResponseTimeRequestClass-a-: A response time goal in milliseconds. You can either define a response time goal or keep the -1 default value, which acts as a placeholder for the response time goal. By doing so, you have not defined the response time goal at run time but can define one later.
a-GracefulShutdownTimeoutNumOfThreadDump: Graceful Shutdown Timeout Num Of Thread Dump
a-GracefulShutdownTimeoutThreadDumpInter: Graceful Shutdown Timeout Thread Dump Interval
a-GroupFromUserFilterForMemberuid-label: Group From User Filter For Member UID
f-SelfTuning_ContextRequestClass_Context: The name of the user group whose requests are to be processed by the request class with the name specified in RequestClassName.
a-HangDetectionMaxTestWaitSeconds-label: Hang Detection Max Test Wait Seconds
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The amount of time to wait for connection tests to complete before the connection pool determines that a connection test is hung. Setting the value to 0 disables the hang detection feature.
a-HeapDumpingOnMaxStuckThread-label: Heap Dumping On Max Stuck Thread
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The maximum number of connection requests that can concurrently block threads while waiting to reserve a connection from the data source's connection pool.
f-JMSServer-a-HostingTemporaryDestinatio: Specifies whether this JMS server can be used to host temporary destinations.
a-IdentityAssertionDoNotCacheContextElem: Identity Assertion Do Not Cache Context Element
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: Enables identity-based-connection-pooling for the data source. When an application requests a database connection, WebLogic Server picks or creates a physical connection with requested DBMS identity based on a map of WebLogic user IDs and database IDs. You must also specify the map of WebLogic Server user IDs to database user IDs (credential mapping).
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-IdentityKey: The path and file name of the identity keystore. The path name must either be absolute or relative to where the server was booted. The identity key store file name is only used if KeystoreLocation is "Custom Stores".
The custom identity keystore passphrase. If empty or null, then the keystore will be opened without a passphrase. This attribute is only used if KeyStores is "Custom Stores".
f-MessagingBridge-a-IdleTimeMaximum-help: The maximum amount of time, in seconds, that a messaging bridge instance remains idle. In asynchronous mode, this is the longest amount of time a messaging bridge instance stays idle before it checks the sanity of its connection to the source. In synchronous mode, this is the amount of time the messaging bridge can block on a receive call if no transaction is involved.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: Check if ignore hostname verification is set. In Secured Production Mode, Coherence hostname verification is enabled by default. If WebLogic isHostnameVerificationIgnored is set, then Coherence will inherit it through this property.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: Enables the data source to be shutdown even if connections obtained from the pool are still in use.
f-SelfTuning_WorkManager-a-IgnoreStuckTh: Specifies whether this Work Manager ignores "stuck" threads. Typically, stuck threads will cause the associated Work Manager to take some action: either switching the application to Admin mode, shutting down the server, or shutting down the Work Manager. If this flag is set, then no thread in this Work Manager is ever considered stuck.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The number of inactive seconds on a reserved connection before WebLogic Server reclaims the connection and releases it back into the connection pool. You can use the Inactive Connection Timeout feature to reclaim leaked connections - connections that were not explicitly closed by the application. Note that this feature is not intended to be used in place of properly closing connections. When set to 0, the feature is disabled.
f-SAFAgent-a-IncomingPausedAtStartup-hel: Specifies whether the agent is paused for incoming messages at startup time. When enabled, the sending agent accepts new messages. Otherwise, the sending agent does not accept any new messages. If the value is changed and activated, you need to restart any servers to which the MBean is targeted before the value will take effect.
a-IncompleteWorkExpirationTime-help: Specifies the maximum length of time, in milliseconds, before undelivered messages in an incomplete UOW are expired. Such messages will then follow the expiration policy defined for undeliverable messages. Note: An error destination for UOW messages cannot be configured with a Unit-of-Work Handling Policy of Single Message Delivery value. This attribute is effective only if the Unit-of-Work Handling Policy is set to Single Message Delivery value. A value of -1 means that UOW messages will never expire.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: Specifies the maximum amount of time, in milliseconds, before undelivered messages in an incomplete UOW are expired. Such messages will then follow the template's expiration policy defined for undeliverable messages. Note: A template's error destination for UOW messages cannot be configured to use the Single Message Delivery value.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: SQL statement to execute that will initialize newly created physical database connections. Start the statement with SQL followed by a space. If the Init SQL value begins with "SQL ", then the rest of the string following that leading token will be taken as a literal SQL statement that will be used to initialize database connections. If the Init SQL value does not begin with "SQL ", the value will be treated as the name of a table and the following SQL statement will be used to initialize connections: "select count(*) from InitSQL"
f-FileStore-a-InitialBootDelaySeconds-he: Specifies the amount of time, in seconds, to delay before starting a cluster-targeted JMS instance on a newly booted WebLogic Server instance. When this setting is configured on a store, it applies to all JMS artifacts that reference the store. This allows time for the system to stabilize and dependent services to be restarted, preventing a system failure during a reboot. A value > 0 is the time, in seconds, to delay before before loading resources after a failure and restart. A value of 0 specifies no delay.
f-JDBCStore-a-InitialBootDelaySeconds-he: Specifies the amount of time, in seconds, to delay before starting a cluster-targeted JMS instance on a newly booted WebLogic Server instance. When this setting is configured on a store, it applies to all JMS artifacts that reference the store. This allows time for the system to stabilize and dependent services to be restarted, preventing a system failure during a reboot. A value > 0 is the time, in seconds, to delay before before loading resources after a failure and restart. A value of 0 specifies no delay.
f-MessagingBridge-a-InitialBootDelaySeco: Specifies the amount of time, in seconds, to delay before starting a cluster-targeted JMS instance on a newly booted WebLogic Server instance. When this setting is configured on a store, it applies to all JMS artifacts that reference the store. This allows time for the system to stabilize and dependent services to be restarted, preventing a system failure during a reboot. A value > 0 is the time, in seconds, to delay before before loading resources after a failure and restart. A value of 0 specifies no delay.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The number of physical connections to create when creating the connection pool in the data source. If unable to create this number of connections, creation of the data source will fail.
f-JMSBridgeDestination-a-InitialContextF: The initial context factory class name for this JMS bridge destination. The default value is weblogic.jndi.WLInitialContextFactory.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_ForeignS: The name of the class that must be instantiated to access the JNDI provider. This class name depends on the JNDI provider and the vendor that are being used. This value corresponds to the standard JNDI property, java.naming.factory.initial. Note: This value defaults to weblogic.jndi.WLInitialContextFactory, which is the correct value for WebLogic Server.
f-ForeignJNDIProvider-a-InitialContextFa: The initial context factory to use to connect. This class name depends on the JNDI provider and the vendor you are using. The value corresponds to the standard JNDI property, java.naming.factory.initial.
f-FileStore-a-InitialSize-help: The initial file size, in bytes.
a-InsertionPausedAtStartup-help: Specifies whether new message insertion is paused on a destination at startup.
f-JMSServer-a-InsertionPausedAtStartup-h: Indicates whether insertion is paused at startup on destinations targeted to this JMS server. A destination cannot receive any new messages while it is paused. When the value is set to true, then immediately after the host server instance is booted, then this JMS server and its targeted destinations are modified such that they are in a "insertion paused" state, which results preventing messages that are result of the "in-flight" work completion to arrive on those destinations.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: Specifies whether new message insertion is paused on destinations that use this template at server startup.
f-JDBCStore-a-InsertsPerBatchMaximum-hel: The maximum number of table rows that are inserted per database call. The default value is 20.
f-Application-a-InstallDir-help: The path to the application's install-root directory, relative to the domain/config/deployments directory. When the installation directory is specified, SourcePath, PlanDir, and PlanPath are derived from this path and need not be specified. The default value for this is the name of the deployment.
a-InterClusterCommLinkHealthCheckInterva: Inter Cluster Comm Link Health Check Interval
a-InternalAppsDeployOnDemandEnabled-labe: Internal Apps Deploy On Demand Enabled
a-Interoperate-help: Specifies whether this local Tuxedo access point interoperates with remote Tuxedo access points that are based upon Tuxedo release 6.5. If this value is set to Yes, the local Tuxedo access point interoperates with a Tuxedo 6.5 domain.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: When true, and when a JDBC 4.3 compatible driver is used, the connection pool will invoke Connection.beginRequest() prior to returning the connection to the application, and will invoke Connection.endRequest() before the connection is released to the pool.
f-FileStore-IoBufferSize-help: The I/O buffer size, in bytes, automatically rounded down to the nearest power of 2.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: Specifies level of JDBC debugging for XA drivers, where larger values in the range provide more debugging information.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The JNDI Name for this CoherenceCacheConfigMBean.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDa: The JNDI Name for this data source. By default, the JNDI name is the name of the data source.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The JNDI Name for this JMS connection factory. The global JNDI name used to look up a connection factory within a clustered JNDI namespace. In a clustered environment, this name is propagated to the entire cluster. If you want the JNDI name to be bound only on the local server, and not propagated to the rest of the cluster, then use the Local JNDI Name setting. If not specified, then the connection factory is not bound into a clustered JNDI namespace.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Queue-a-: The JNDI Name for this JMS queue. The global JNDI name used to look up a connection factory within a clustered JNDI namespace. In a clustered environment, this name is propagated to the entire cluster. If you want the JNDI name to be bound only on the local server, and not propagated to the rest of the cluster, then use the Local JNDI Name setting. If not specified, then the connection factory is not bound into a clustered JNDI namespace.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Topic-a-: The JNDI Name for this JMS topic. The global JNDI name used to look up a connection factory within a clustered JNDI namespace. In a clustered environment, this name is propagated to the entire cluster. If you want the JNDI name to be bound only on the local server, and not propagated to the rest of the cluster, then use the Local JNDI Name setting. If not specified, then the connection factory is not bound into a clustered JNDI namespace.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_UniformD: The JNDI Name for this JMS uniform distributed queue. The global JNDI name used to look up a connection factory within a clustered JNDI namespace. In a clustered environment, this name is propagated to the entire cluster. If you want the JNDI name to be bound only on the local server, and not propagated to the rest of the cluster, then use the Local JNDI Name setting. If not specified, then the connection factory is not bound into a clustered JNDI namespace.

The JNDI Name for this JMS uniform distributed topic. The global JNDI name used to look up a connection factory within a clustered JNDI namespace. In a clustered environment, this name is propagated to the entire cluster. If you want the JNDI name to be bound only on the local server, and not propagated to the rest of the cluster, then use the Local JNDI Name setting. If not specified, then the connection factory is not bound into a clustered JNDI namespace.
f-MailSession-a-JNDIName-help: The JNDI Name for this JavaMail session.
a-JNDIPrefix-help: Specifies the string that will prefix the local JNDI name of a remote destination.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_ForeignS: Any Credentials that must be set for the JNDI provider. These Credentials will be part of the properties will be passed directly to the constructor for the JNDI provider's InitialContext class. Some foreign providers require other properties to be set while obtaining an initial naming context. These properties can be set with a JNDIProperty bean.
f-EJBContainer-a-JavaCompiler-help: The path to the Java compiler to use to compile EJBs (e.g. "sj" or "javac"). Note: the default must be null. If no JavaCompiler is specified on this specific EJBComponent, the default will be pulled in the following order from - EJBContainerMBean - Server.JavaCompiler.
f-EJBContainer-a-JavaCompilerPostClassPa: Provides a list of the options to append to the Java compiler classpath when you compile Java code.
f-EJBContainer-a-JavaCompilerPreClassPat: Provides a list of the options to prepend to the Java compiler classpath when you compile Java code.
a-JavaStandardTrustKeyStorePassPhrase-la: Java Standard Trust Key Store Passphrase
a-JavaStandardTrustKeyStorePassPhraseEnc: Java Standard Trust Key Store Passphrase Encrypted
a-JmsConnectionFactoryUnmappedResRefMode: JMS Connection Factory Unmapped Res Ref Mode
a-JmsCreateDestinationIdentifier-help: A reference name for a destination or a member of a distributed destination that provides a way to lookup that destination without JNDI using jakarta.jms.Session createQueue or createTopic. See "How to Lookup a Destination" in Programming JMS for more information on how to use this attribute. This name must be unique within the scope of the JMS server to which this destination is targeted. However, it does not need to be unique within the scope of an entire JMS module or WebLogic Cluster. For example, two queues can have the same destination name as long as those queues are targeted to different JMS servers. Note: Since this name must be unique within the scope of a JMS server, verify whether other JMS modules may contain destination names that conflict with this name. It is the responsibility of the deployer to resolve the destination names targeted to JMS servers.
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeGlobal-a-JmsFactor: The name of the JMS connection factory; for example, weblogic.jndi.ConnectionFactory.  The default value is weblogic.jms.XAConnectionFactory.
a-JmsToTuxPriorityMap-help: The mapping of priorities from JMS to Tuxedo. The default JMS To Tux Priority Map is: 0:1 | 1:12 | 2:23 | 3:34 | 4:45 |5:56 | 6:67 | 7:78 | 8:89 | 9:100.
a-JndiFactory-label: JNDI Initial Context Factory Class Name
f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeGlobal-a-JndiFacto: The name of the JNDI lookup factory. The default value is weblogic.jndi.WLInitialContextFactory.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-KeepAlive-h: Return value tells whether this local Tuxedo access point is configured with Application Level Keep Alive, and it maximum idle time value before wait timer start ticking.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-KeepAlive-: Indicates whether this remote Tuxedo access point is configured with Application Level Keep Alive. Greater than 0 means that the application-level Keep Alive is enabled and the value indicates the amount of idle time, in milliseconds rounded to the nearest second, allowed before starting the wait timer.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-KeepAliveWa: Return value that tells whether this local Tuxedo access point requires the acknowledgement of Application Level Keep Alive, and how long it will wait without receiving acknowledgement before declare the connection is inaccessible.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-KeepAliveW: Indicates whether this remote Tuxedo access point requires the acknowledgement of Application Level Keep Alive. A value of 0 indicates that application-level Keep Alive is not enabled for the access point but the access point acknowledges if a heartbeat is received. A value greater than 0 indicates that application-level Keep Alive is enabled and the value indicates the amount of idle time, in milliseconds rounded to the nearest second, allowed before WebLogic Tuxedo Connector marks the connection as failed if the heartbeat is not acknowledged.
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCDa: Enables WebLogic Server to keep the physical database connection associated with the logical connection when committing a global transaction instead releasing it and getting another physical connection when needed. Setting this option to true may require additional connections to be configured on the database. Use this setting to work around specific problems with JDBC XA drivers.
f-EJBContainer-a-KeepGenerated-help: Specifies whether KeepGenerated is enabled and the EJB compiler source files will be kept.
a-KeepLogicalConnOpenOnRelease-label: Keep Logical Connection Open On Release
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCXA: Enables WebLogic Server to keep the logical JDBC connection open for a global transaction when the physical XA connection is returned to the connection pool. Select this option if the XA driver used to create database connections or the DBMS requires that a logical JDBC connection be kept open while transaction processing continues (although the physical XA connection can be returned to the connection pool). Only applies to data sources that use an XA driver. Use this setting to work around specific problems with JDBC XA drivers.
a-KeepXaConnTillTxComplete-label: Keep XA Connection Until Transaction Completes
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCXA: Enables WebLogic Server to associate the same XA database connection from the connection pool with a global transaction until the transaction completes. Only applies to connection pools that use an XA driver. Use this setting to work around specific problems with JDBC XA drivers.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_ForeignS: The name of the JNDI property.
f-JoltConnectionPool-a-KeyStoreName-help: The path and file name of the identity keystore containing the private key used in SSL mutual authentication.
f-JoltConnectionPool-a-KeyStorePassPhras: The identity keystore passphrase. If empty or null, then the keystore will be opened without a passphrase.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-KeyStoresLo: Provides the configuration rule to be used for finding Local Access Point's identity key store and trust key store. In plain text, it contains information on where the identity key store and trust key store are configured. When KeyStoreLocation is configured with WLS Store, WTC uses configuration information from the WLS Key Stores configuration. Otherwise, it uses the key stores information configured in the Local Access Point.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Destinat: The expected property type for this destination key.
a-ListenAddress-help: The DNS name or IP address.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The listen port. Deprecated in 12.2.1 since the well-known address no longer needs a port to bne specified.
f-StartupClass-a-LoadAfterAppsRunning-he: Specifies whether the targeted servers load and run this startup class after applications and EJBs are running. If you enable this feature for a startup class, a server loads and runs the startup class after the activate phase. At this point, JMS and JDBC services are available. (Deployment for applications and EJBs consists of three phases: prepare, admin and activate.)
a-LoadBalancingEnabled-help: Specifies whether non-anonymous producers created through a connection factory are load balanced within a distributed destination on a per-call basis.
a-LoadBalancingPolicy-help: Determines how messages are distributed to the members of this destination. Note: This attribute is ignored by standalone/singleton queues and topics, it only applies to distributed destinations.
f-StartupClass-a-LoadBeforeAppActivation: Specifies whether the targeted servers load and run this startup class after activating JMS and JDBC services and before activating applications and EJBs. If you enable this feature for a startup class, a server loads and runs the startup class before the activate phase. At this point, JMS and JDBC services are available. (Deployment for applications and EJBs consists of three phases: prepare, admin and activate.)
f-StartupClass-a-LoadBeforeAppDeployment: Specifies whether the targeted servers load and run this startup class before activating JMS and JDBC services and before starting deployment for applications and EJBs. If you enable this feature for a startup class, a server loads and runs the startup class before the deployment prepare phase. At this point, JMS and JDBC services are not yet available. (Deployment for applications and EJBs consists of three phases: prepare, admin and activate.)
a-LoadStubUsingContextClassLoader-label: Load Stub Using Context Class Loader
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-LocalAcces: The local domain name from which this remote Tuxedo domain is reached.
f-WTCServer_WTCExport-a-LocalAccessPoint: The name of the local access point that exports this service.
f-WTCServer_WTCImport-a-LocalAccessPoint: The name of the local access point that offers this service.
f-WTCServer_WTCPassword-a-LocalAccessPoi: The name of the local access point to which this password applies.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The local JNDI name used to look up the connection factory within the JNDI namespace of the server where the connection factory is targeted. In a clustered environment, this name is bound only on the local server instance and is not propagated to the rest of the cluster. If not specified, then the connection factory is not bound into the local JNDI namespace.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_ForeignS: The name that the remote object will be bound to in the local server's JNDI tree. This is the name that should be used to look up the object on the local server.
The name that the remote object will be bound to in the local server's JNDI tree. This is the name that should be used to look up the object on the local server.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Queue-a-: The local JNDI name used to look up the destination within the JNDI namespace of the server where the destination resource is targeted. In a clustered environment, this name is bound only on the local server instance and is not propagated to the rest of the cluster. A destination can have both a local JNDI name and a (global) JNDI name.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_SAFImpor: The local JNDI name of the remote destination.
The local JNDI name of the remote destination.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Topic-a-: The local JNDI name used to look up the destination within the JNDI namespace of the server where the destination resource is targeted. In a clustered environment, this name is bound only on the local server instance and is not propagated to the rest of the cluster. A destination can have both a local JNDI name and a (global) JNDI name.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_UniformD: The local JNDI name used to look up the destination within the JNDI namespace of the server where the destination resource is targeted. In a clustered environment, this name is bound only on the local server instance and is not propagated to the rest of the cluster. A destination can have both a local JNDI name and a (global) JNDI name.

The local JNDI name used to look up the destination within the JNDI namespace of the server where the destination resource is targeted. In a clustered environment, this name is bound only on the local server instance and is not propagated to the rest of the cluster. A destination can have both a local JNDI name and a (global) JNDI name.
f-ForeignJNDIProvider_ForeignJNDILink-a-: The JNDI name that the foreign JNDI object will be bound to in the local JNDI namespace.
f-WTCServer_WTCPassword-a-LocalPassword-: The local password used to authenticate connections between the local access point and the remote access point. Note that this password is used to authenticate connections between the local Tuxedo access point identified by LocalAccessPoint and the remote Tuxedo access point identified by RemoteAccessPoint.
f-WTCServer_WTCPassword-a-LocalPasswordI: The initialization vector used to encrypt the local password.
f-JMSServer_JmsMessageLogFile-a-LogFileR: The directory where the rotated log files will be stored. By default the rotated files are stored in the same directory where the log file is stored.
f-SAFAgent_JmssafMessageLogFile-a-LogFil: The directory where the rotated log files will be stored. By default the rotated files are stored in the same directory where the log file is stored.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_SAFError: Specifies how information is logged when Message Handling Policy is set to Log. When specifying multiple values, enter them as a comma-separated list. The %header% and %properties% values are not case sensitive. For example, you could use "%header%,%properties%" for all the JMS header fields and user properties. However, the enumeration of individual JMS header fields and user-defined properties are case sensitive. To enumerate only individual JMS header fields you could use "%header, name, address, city, state, zip". Note: The JMSMessageID field is always logged and cannot be turned off. Therefore, if the Log Format is not defined (i.e., null) or is defined as an empty string, then the output to the log file contains only the JMSMessageID of the message.
a-LogMonitoringMaxThrottleMessageSignatu: Log Monitoring Max Throttle Message Signature Count
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The logger name for Coherence logs.
f-SAFAgent-a-LoggingEnabled-help: Specifies whether a message is logged in the server log file when a message fails to be forwarded. If selected, this applies to messages that fail to be forwarded and delivered to the final destination when there is no error handling in a SAF application or the application's error handling fails.
f-FileStore-a-LogicalName-help: The name used by subsystems to refer to different stores on different servers using the same name. For example, an EJB that uses the timer service may refer to its store using the logical name, and this name may be valid on multiple servers in the same cluster, even if each server has a store with a different physical name. Multiple stores in the same domain or the same cluster may share the same logical name. However, a given logical name may not be assigned to more than one store on the same server.
f-JDBCStore-a-LogicalName-help: The name used by subsystems to refer to different stores on different servers using the same name. For example, an EJB that uses the timer service may refer to its store using the logical name, and this name may be valid on multiple servers in the same cluster, even if each server has a store with a different physical name. Multiple stores in the same domain or the same cluster may share the same logical name. However, a given logical name may not be assigned to more than one store on the same server.
a-LoginAttemptsWhileLockedTotalCount-lab: Login Attempts While Locked Total Count
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The number of seconds to delay before creating each physical database connection. This delay supports database servers that cannot handle multiple connection requests in rapid succession. The delay takes place both during initial data source creation and during the lifetime of the data source whenever a physical database connection is created.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_SAFRemot: Specifies the URL to connect to when using this SAF Login Context. SAFImportedDestinations are associated with a SAFRemoteContext that has a SAFLoginContext. This SAFLoginContext defines the URL to use to connect.
f-ManagedExecutorServiceTemplate-a-LongR: An integer that specifies the long-running daemon thread's priority. If a value is specified, all long-running threads are affected.
f-ManagedScheduledExecutorServiceTemplat: An integer that specifies the long-running daemon thread's priority. If a value is specified, all long-running threads are affected.
a-MBEncodingMapFile-help: The encoding name map file between Java and Tuxedo MBSTRING.
a-MagicThreadDumpBackToSocket-label: Magic Thread Dump Back To Socket
f-JDBCSystemResource_JdbcResource_JDBCCo: The maximum number of physical connections that this connection pool can contain.
f-ManagedExecutorServiceTemplate-a-MaxCo: The maximum number of running long-running tasks submitted to this Concurrent Managed Object (CMO).
f-ManagedScheduledExecutorServiceTemplat: The maximum number of running long-running tasks submitted to this Concurrent Managed Object (CMO).
f-ManagedThreadFactoryTemplate-a-MaxConc: The maximum number of concurrent new threads that can be created by this Managed Thread Factory (MTF).
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-MaxEncryptB: The maximum encryption key length (in bits) this local Tuxedo access point uses when establishing a session connection. A value of 0 indicates no encryption is used.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-MaxEncrypt: The maximum encryption key length (in bits) this remote Tuxedo access point uses when establishing a session connection. A value of 0 indicates no encryption is used.
f-FileStore-a-MaxFileSize-help: The maximum file size, in bytes, of an individual data file. A small number of larger files is normally preferred over a large number of smaller files as each file allocates Window Buffer and file handles. If MaxFileSize is larger than 2^24 * BlockSize, then MaxFileSize is ignored, and the value becomes 2^24 * BlockSize. The default BlockSize is 512, and 2^24 * 512 is 8 GB.
f-WTCServer_WTCLocalTuxDom-a-MaxRetries-: The maximum number of times that this local Tuxedo access point tries to establish a session connection to remote Tuxedo access points. Use this value only when Connection Policy is set to ON_STARTUP. The default value is 9223372036854775807.
f-WTCServer_WTCRemoteTuxDom-a-MaxRetries: The maximum encryption key length (in bits) this remote Tuxedo access point uses when establishing a session connection. A value of 0 indicates no encryption is used. Note that when the ConnectionPolicy value is LOCAL, the MaxRetries value from the local Tuxedo access point is used. When the ConnectionPolicy value is ON_STARTUP, a value of -1 indicates 9223372036854775807.
a-MaxRetrySecondsBeforeDeterminerFail-la: Max Retry Seconds Before Determiner Fail

f-JMSServer-a-MaximumMessageSize-help: The maximum number of bytes allowed in individual messages on this JMS server. Messages that are redirected to an error destination or forwarded to a member of a distributed destination are not checked for size.
f-SAFAgent-a-MaximumMessageSize-help: The maximum number of bytes allowed in individual messages on this SAF agent. The message size includes the message body, any user-defined properties, and the user-defined JMS header fields: JMSCorrelationID and JMSType. The maximum message size is only enforced for the initial production of a message. f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Queue-a-: The maximum size of a message that is accepted from producers on this destination. The message size includes the message body, any user-defined properties, and the user-defined JMS header fields: JMSCorrelationID and JMSType. Producers sending messages that exceed the configured maximum message size for the destination receive a ResourceAllocationException. The maximum message size is only enforced for the initial production of a message. Messages that are redirected to an error destination or forwarded to a member of a distributed destination are not checked for size. For instance, if a destination and its corresponding error destination are configured with a maximum message size of 128K bytes and 64K bytes, respectively, a message of 96K bytes could be redirected to the error destination (even though it exceeds the 64K byte maximum), but a producer could not directly send the 96K byte message to the error destination.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: The maximum size of a message that will be accepted from producers a destination using this template. f-JoltConnectionPool-a-MaximumPoolSize-h: The maximum number of connections that can be made from this Jolt connection pool.
f-JMSServer-a-MessageBufferSize-help: The amount of memory (in bytes) that this JMS server can use to store message bodies before it writes them to disk. When the JMS server writes the message bodies to disk, it clears them from memory. A value of -1 (the default) specifies that the server will automatically determine a size based on the maximum heap size of the JVM. This default will be set to either one-third the maximum heap size, or 512 megabytes, whichever is smaller.
f-SAFAgent-a-MessageBufferSize-help: The amount of memory (in bytes) that this SAF agent can use to store message bodies in memory before they are paged out to disk. A value of -1 (the default) specifies that the server will automatically determine a size based on the maximum heap size of the JVM. This default will be set to either one-third the maximum heap size, or 512 megabytes, whichever is smaller.
f-JMSServer-a-MessageCompressionOptions-: Specifies the type of message compression used when JMS message body compression is enabled for Persistent Stores and JMS Paging Stores.
f-SAFAgent-a-MessageCompressionOptions-h: Specifies the type of message compression used when JMS message body compression is enabled for Persistent Stores and JMS Paging Stores.
f-CoherenceClusterSystemResource_Coheren: The Coherence logs message format.
a-MessageLoggingEnabled-help: Specifies whether the module logs information about the message life cycle.
a-MessageLoggingFormat-help: Defines which information about the message is logged. When specifying multiple values, enter them as a comma-separated list. The %header% and %properies% values are not case sensitive. For example, you could use "%header%,%properties%" for all the JMS header fields and user properties. However, the enumeration of individual JMS header fields and user-defined properties are case sensitive. To enumerate only individual JMS header fields you could use "%header, name, address, city, state, zip". Note: The JMSMessageID field is always logged and cannot be turned off. Therefore, if the Message Logging Format is not defined (i.e., null) or is defined as an empty string, then the output to the log file contains only the JMSMessageID of the message. Gets the message-logging-format element.
a-MessagesHigh-help: The upper threshold (total number of messages in this destination) that triggers logging or flow control events. The value of java.lang.Long.MAX_VALUE disables logging and flow control events for the destination.
a-MessagesLimitOverride-help: The maximum number of messages that can be stored in a topic subscription. If a new message arrives on subscriptions that have reached the specified limit, then the first-most available messages on these subscriptions will be deleted to make room for the new message. Subscription messages are immune from this deletion if they're participating in a pending transaction, have already been passed to a consumer and are awaiting acknowledgement, or if they are part of a Unit-of-Work that is still waiting to accumulate all of its messages. Note that if all messages are immune from deletion, then a new message can cause a subscription size to exceed its limit. A value of -1 means no limit override.
a-MessagesLow-help: The lower threshold (total number of messages in this destination) that triggers logging or flow control events. The value of java.lang.Long.MAX_VALUE disables logging and flow control events for the destination.
f-JMSServer-a-MessagesMaximum-help: The maximum number of messages that can be stored in this JMS server. A value of -1 removes any WebLogic Server limits.
f-SAFAgent-a-MessagesMaximum-help: The maximum message quota (total amount of messages) that can be stored in this SAF agent. The default value of -1 specifies that the server instance has no limit on the number of messages that can be stored.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Connecti: The maximum number of messages that can exist for an asynchronous session and that have not yet been passed to the message listener. When the Synchronous Prefetch Mode is enabled, this value also affects synchronous sessions with a message consumer that will prefetch messages in one server access. A value of -1 indicates that there is no limit on the number of messages. In this case, however, the limit is set to the amount of remaining virtual memory.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Quota-a-: The total number of bytes that can be stored in a destination that uses this quota. A value of zero means that no messages can be placed on a destination without exceeding the quota. A value of -1 prevents WebLogic Server from imposing a limit.
f-JMSServer-a-MessagesThresholdHigh-help: The upper threshold (number of messages stored in this JMS server) that triggers flow control and logging events. A value of -1 disables the events for this JMS server.
f-SAFAgent-a-MessagesThresholdHigh-help: The upper threshold that triggers events based on the number of messages stored in the SAF agent. The default value of -1 disables the events for this SAF agent.
f-JMSServer-a-MessagesThresholdLow-help: The lower threshold (number of messages stored in this JMS server) that triggers flow control and logging events. A value of -1 disables the events for this JMS server.
f-SAFAgent-a-MessagesThresholdLow-help: The low threshold that triggers events based on the number of messages stored in the SAF agent. A value of -1 disables the events for this SAF agent.
a-MessagingPerformancePreference-help: Controls how long destinations are willing to wait to create full batches of available messages (if at all) for delivery to consumers. At the minimum value, batching is disabled; at the default value, less-than-full batches will not wait and are delivered immediately with currently available messages; tuning higher than the default value controls the maximum wait time for additional messages before less-than-full batches are delivered to consumers. The maximum message count of a full batch is controlled by the JMS connection factory's Messages Maximum setting.
f-JMSSystemResource_JmsResource_Template: Controls how long destinations that use this template are willing to wait to create full batches of available messages (if at all) for delivery to consumers. At the minimum value, batching is disabled; at the default value, less-than-full batches will not wait and are delivered immediately with currently available messages; tuning higher than the default value controls the maximum wait time for additional messages before less-than-full batches are delivered to consumers. f-WTCServer_WTCtBridgeRedirect-a-MetaDat: The name of the metadata file URL used to pass the call to the XML-to-non-XML WebLogic XML Translator (WLXT).
f-FileStore-a-MigrationPolicy-help: Controls migration and restart behavior of cluster-targeted JMS service artifact instances. f-JDBCStore-a-MigrationPolicy-help: Controls migration and restart behavior of cluster-targeted JMS service artifact instances. f-MessagingBridge-a-MigrationPolicy-help: Controls migration and restart behavior of cluster-targeted JMS service artifact instances. f-SingletonService-a-MillisToSleepBetwee: Controls how long of a pause there should be between the migration attempts described in getAdditionalMigrationAttempts(). a-MillisToSleepBetweenAutoMigrationAttem: Milliseconds To Sleep Between Auto Migration Attempts

f-JMSServer_JmsMessageLogFile-a-NumberOf: Indicates whether to limit the number of log files that this server instance creates to store old messages. If you do not enable this option, the server creates new files indefinitely and you must clean up these files as you require.
f-SAFAgent_JmssafMessageLogFile-a-Number: Indicates whether to limit the number of log files that this server instance creates to store old messages. f-FileStore-a-NumberOfRestartAttempts-he: Specifies the maximum number of restart attempts. A value > 0 specifies the maximum number of restart attempts. f-JDBCStore-a-NumberOfRestartAttempts-he: Specifies the maximum number of restart attempts. A value > 0 specifies the maximum number of restart attempts. a-OneWaySendMode-help: Specifies whether message producers created using this connection factory are allowed to do one-way message sends to improve typical non-persistent, non-transactional messaging performance. When enabled, the associated queue senders and/or topic publishers can send messages without internally waiting for a response from the target destination's host JMS server.
a-OneWaySendWindowSize-help: Specifies the maximum number of sent messages per window when One-Way Send Mode is set to allow queue senders and/or topic publishers to make one-way sends. The window size determines when a two-way message is required to regulate the producer before it can continue making additional one-way sends. To benefit from one-way performance, the default One-Way Send Window Size value must be configured higher in addition to enabling one-way sends. After every OneWaySendWindowSize - 1 number of messages, a two-way is used instead of a one-way, so all messages are actually two-way when the OneWaySendWindowSize = 1.
